    <p><img src="/images/sunny_beach.svg" class="square_left" alt="sunny beach">
    To communicate verbally or in written form about the concept of “happiness”, writers must use a lot of words to communicate. Since words are subjective, sequential, and subject to structural rules, they are very good when precise meaning is possible, but less effective when multiple meanings are needed to be conveyed simultaneously.
    </p>
    <p>This is not to say that drawing is more precise than words all the time, but that they are more dense. They can convey more ideas in a shorter span of time than words can. For this reason, drawing ideas, especially complex ones, is often more efficient than trying to describe them with words. Even if someone is not practiced at drawing, the act of drawing itself allows the descriptive words to become more precise as the team discusses the ideas depicted. This is helpful for getting
      everyone on the same page as well as for starting to explore design ideas.</p>

    <h2>This is Just Show And Tell</h2>
    <p>In grade school, many students in the United States engaged in a game called “Show and Tell”. In this exercise, students brought in an object they thought was interesting, show it to the class, and then tell the class something about that object.
    </p>
    <p>One of the purposes of this exercise is to teach students about representational forms: although a student cannot bring the hike in the woods with their parent to class, they can bring the cool rocks they picked up on that hike to class as a
      representation of what they did. By connecting the tangible rocks with the intangible hike, students were able to make generalizable connections about the elements of a hike, where to find rocks, and what future hikes or rocks might be like.
    </p>
    <p>As adults, images function in the same way: the visualization allows for general communication about an experience, substance, process, etc. that cannot be present. For this reason, the old game of show and tell as useful in meetings as it was in your grade school’s class.
    </p>

    <h3>Using Collections of References</h3>
    Moving on from a single reference for happiness, designers often use collections of references, called "reference decks", to communicate multi-faceted or complex ideas for a system, product, or service design. These reference decks have four primary goals:
      <br>
      <ul class="usa-list">
        <li>To
          <strong>explore</strong>
          nuances in a proposal, system, or idea</li>
        <li>To
          <strong>understand</strong>
          those nuances</li>
        <li>To
          <strong>clarify</strong>
          those nuances, especially if they act within a complex system</li>
        <li>To
          <strong>communicate</strong>
          the steps above to others who may or may not be present</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Important to note: this is not a rigid sequence of steps, but is instead a collection of images, sounds, or models in no particular order. There is no pressure to create a story of the solution at this juncture. Instead, reference decks allow the designer themselves or the design team to communicate their ideas for solutions.
      </p>

